of negative campaigning to date, The Positive Case for Negative Campaigning uses models, surveys, and experiments to show that much of the seeming dislike of negative campaigning can be explained by the way survey questions have been worded. By failing to distinguish between baseless and credible attacks, surveys fail to capture differences in voters’ receptivity. Voters’ responses, the authors argue, vary greatly and can be better explained by the content and believability of the ads than by whether the ads are negative. Mattes and Redlawsk continue on to establish how voters make use of negative information and why it is necessary. Many voters are politically naïve and unlikely to make inferences about candidates’ positions or traits, so the ability of candidates to go on the attack and focus explicitly on information that would not otherwise be available is crucial to voter education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCampaign literature - United States. 0aCampaign literature -- United States. 0aCampaign literaturezUnited States. 0aMass media -- Political aspects -- United States. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aNegativism. 0aPolitical campaigns -- United States. 0aPolitical campaignszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aelections, campaign, attack ads, negative campaigning, political science, politics, nonfiction, electorate, voters, politicians, candidates, television, social media, endorsements, negativity, voter turnout, engagement, activism, credibility, character, lies, confidence, trust, authority, belief, believability, information, surveys, slander, libel, truth, facts.1 aMancevski, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRedlawsk, David P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part